I am so humbled and thrilled when I just heard the news, thank you very much. It is a prize given to Africa, given to Ethiopia, and I can imagine how the rest of Africa's leaders will take it positively to work on the peace-building process on our continent." Egypt's President Abdul Fattah al-Sisi has shared his congratulations. He described the awarding of the price as a "new victory for our ambitious continent, for peace and for efforts for achieving stability and development. Kenya's President, Uhuru Kenyatta, has said that Ahmed deserves the international recognition that comes with winning the Nobel Peace Prize, saying, “he stands out as a relentless champion for peace, stability and prosperity of his country, our region and the entire African continent.” Other African leaders who reacted to the award are Nigeria's President Muhammadu Buhari, South Africa's President Cyril Ramaphosa, Ghana's President Nana Akufo-Addo and Liberia's President George Weah, who all hailed peace and stability as the ingredients to Africa moving to greater heights. Ethiopia's Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed has become the 12th African person to win the Nobel Peace Prize. It has been awarded 100 times - to 107 people and 27 organisations. Previous African winners were: 2018 - Dennis Mukwege - Democratic Republic of Congo 2015 - National Dialogue Quartet - Tunisia 2011 - Ellen Johnson Sirleaf and Leymah Gbowee - Liberia 2005 - Mohamed El Baradei - Egypt 2004 - Wangari Maathai - Kenya 2001 - Kofi Annan - Ghana 1993 - Nelson Mandela and FW de Klerk - South Africa 1984 - Desmond Tutu - South Africa 1978 - Anwar al-Sadat - Egypt 1960 - Albert Lutuli - South Africa --BBC--